         <abstract id="aspace_b2464ed56476238ce48e3c3db920a94f">This collection draws together documentation relating to educational and medical institutions and organizations that were established by mission agencies and World Christian churches. It complements other substantial archival collections held by the Divinity Library.</abstract>
         <origination label="Source">
            <corpname source="local">
               <part localtype="agent_corporate_entity">Yale University. Divinity School. Library</part>
            </corpname>
         </origination>
      </did>
      <arrangement id="aspace_e46f3080c54d737b8d66379b2826cd34">
         <head>Arrangement</head>
         <p>The collection is organized into four series:</p>
         <p>Series I. Educational Institutions</p>
         <p>Series II. Educational Associations and Coordinating Organizations</p>
         <p>Series III. Medical Institutions</p>
         <p>Series IV. Medical Associations and Coordinating Organizations</p>
      </arrangement>
      <bioghist id="aspace_30df5b7d37b8fe52ee7600677daf4b27">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Educational and medical work have been integral parts of the missionary movement and churches formed from that movement. Throughout the world, mission agencies and churches established schools, hospitals, and centers for the treatment of individuals suffering from leprosy (Hansen's disease), mental illness, and blindness.</p>
      </bioghist>
      <accessrestrict id="aspace_4b2631a55b994f7abb40fb8fb18c3d59">
         <head>Conditions Governing Access</head>
         <p>Collection is open for research.</p>
      </accessrestrict>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_f7a48e1a4f6861390ab9fafe336a570f">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>Much of this collection consists of printed or mimeographed reports, memos, brochures and other documentation of the work of the educational and medical instituitons and organizations represented. This material came to the Divinity Library in various ways over the years. The documentation in this collection is not comprehensive but it provides useful background and detail about educational and medical work of mission agencies and the churches formed out of the mission movement, from its beginnings until the present time.  The majority of the material in this collection dates from the 19th and 20th centuries.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      <prefercite id="aspace_aa30e873bc3b254092bc641b28c041cf">
         <head>Preferred Citation</head>
         <p>Records of Mission and World Christian Educational and Medical Institutions and Organizations (RG 347), Special Collections, Yale Divinity Library.</p>
      </prefercite>
